<TITLE> Japan PM says reluctant to call early election </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, Jan 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Japanese Prime Minister Yasuo Fukuda said on Tuesday he was reluctant to call an early general election for fear of affecting the economy, which he said was facing "delicate problems." No election need be held until September 2009, but the policy gridlock caused by the opposition's domination of the less powerful of parliament's two houses has led to speculation that Fukuda's ruling coalition could go to the polls this year. "We have to dissolve parliament some time," Fukuda told a news conference marking the end of the parliamentary session. "It is a question of choosing the right time. We have to make sure dissolving it does not affect people's livelihoods or the economy." Speaking at a news conference following the end of the parliamentary session, also implied that he did not want to hold an election before the G8 summit to be held in Japan in July. "I don't think I should dissolve parliament lightly," Fukuda said. "We must take the whole situation into account and make a decision." The opposition is pushing for a lower house poll after the budget for the fiscal year starting in April is enacted in late March. Budget legislation can be passed without the approval of the upper house. Fukuda said the problems facing the economy made it even more important than usual to pass the budget. With the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's support levels far lower than they were at the time of the last general election, the policy stalemate will not be resolved unless the main opposition Democratic Party wins a majori
